{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060205A/1937110701/0335.xml":{"full_text":"I I FINANCIAL AND CLASSIFIED\nClassified Ads jr\nI IPIjc te e\nPart 4\u201416 Pages WASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, NOVEMBER 7, 1937.\nBUSINESS UNEVEN\nIN FIFTH DISTRICT,\nSURVEY REVEALS\nRetail Sales in Capital Ex\nceed Previous Week, Off\nFrom Year Ago.\nEXTRA HEAVY HOLIDAY\nTRADE NOW PREDICTED\nCapital Transit Stock Shows Frac\ntional Gain From Low Mark\non Exchange.\nBy EDWARD C. STONE.\nRetail trade in Washington and the\nrest of the Fifth Federal Reserve Dis\ntrict during the last week was uneven,\nthe Commerce Department reported\nyesterday. Sales in the Capital's de\npartment stores, despite much un\nfavorable shopping weather, were\n10.63 per cent ahead of the previous\nweek, but declined 7.14 as- cent from\nthe corresponding week last year. The\nweek included a Government pay day.\nBank clearings in Washington\namounted to $25,839,911. against the\nlower figure a year ago of $21,912,263.\nThe commerce survey stated that\nbuilding permits in October totaled\ntl.969.765, in comparison with $2,\n061,975 in October, 1936. There were\nabout 6,000 more tourists In the city\nthan at the same time last year.\nTotal volume of trade in other cities\nIn the fifth district was practically\nunchanged. Gains in some cities were\noffset by losses in others. Charleston.\n8. C.. reported an 8 per cent gain over\nlast year. Return of cooler weather\nand special sales boosted business In\nBaltimore to a mark higher than a\nyear ago.\nAlthough the business outlook is still\nsomewhat uncertain, the commerce\nreport says, retailers generally \"an\nticipate one of the most active holiday\nperiods in the last seven or eight\nyears.\"\ntransit Stork Up Slightly.\nCapital Transit Co. stock closed the\nweek at 8'2 on the Washington Stock\nExchange yesterday, one 10-share sale\nbeing recorded. The final bid was I-\u2019i,\nwith 8-!i asked.\nFollowing the increase in fares\ngranted by the Public Utilities Com\nmission, a tiny sale of two shares of\nTransit stock took place at 8. the\nlowest price the stock has ever reached.\nThe highest price this year was $16 a\nshare. Many years ago the company\u2019s\noriginal stock sold at $100 a share,\noften considerably higher, and paid\na regular dividend of $7 a year.\nIn the bond division Capital Trac\ntion 5s did not appear in yesterday\u2019s\ntrading. Earlier in the week they\nchanged hands at 73, up a point from\nOther recent sales. The market closed\nyesterday with 69 bid for the bonds\nand 75 asked. Early this year they sold\nat 97. Results of the boost In fares\nto six tokens for 50 cents are being\nawaited with deep concern by both\nstock and bond holders. The answer\nWill take time.\nOn the exchange yesterday Wash\nington Gas Light preferred stock\nopened at 99 ex-dividend, and closed\nat 99ij.\nAdams Attacks Managed Money.\nOrval W. Adams aroused a lot of\nInterest in his first address as presi\ndent of the American Bankers As\nsociation. In it he deplored Govern\nment ownership of the Federal sys\ntem now proposed in Congress, assert\ning that it would create a banking\nmonopoly. \u201cThe Federal Reserve\nSystem owned by the Government\ncould and would develop into the\ngreatest monopoly ever created,\u201d he\n\u2022aid.\nHe attacked the proposals to trans\nfer bank supervisory agencies of the\nvarious States to a single Federal\nagency, such as the Federal Deposit\nInsurance Corp. and expressed dis\napproval of any efforts to transfer\nthe functions of the controller of\nthe currency, whose office supervises\nthe national banks. He stated that\n\u201cmoney management has reduced\nInterest rates to so low a point that\nbanks are having difficulty in making\nreasonable earnings.\"\nMr. Adams demanded balancing\nof the Federal budget and congratu\nlated the A. B. A. on its position\n\u2022gainst extension of branch banking\n\u2022cross State lines.\nNoted in Financial District.\nThe Treasury minted $4,282,401.55\nworm oi new coins in October. This\nIncludes $1,568,577 In ordinary half\ndollars, $2,503 In Daniel Boone com\nmemorative half-dollars, $951,125.75\nIn quarters, $85,060,000 in dimes,\n$270,855 in nickels and $604,290.50\nworth of pennies.\nJoshua Evans, jr\u201e vice president\nof the Hamilton National Bank, has\nbeen appointed a member of the\nAmerican Bankers Association Com\nmittee on National Legislation by\nPresident Adams. He will also serve\non a subcommittee on banking.\nM. S. Szymczak, member of the\nFederal Reserve Board, said in Bos\nton Friday that every regulation\nadopted under this administration\nhas had one main purpose, to ease\ncredit, this policy being considered\n\u201cabsolutely necessary to promote eco\nnomic recovery.\u201d\nThe United States Chamber of\nCommerce reports that this country\nnot only leads the world as an actual\nand potential power-using country,\nbut also leads in use of power per\nworker. The Nation uses more than\na third of the world's output of elec\ntrical energy and has nearly a third\nof the world\u2019s developed waterpower.\nREGISTRATION STATEMENTS.\nRegistration statements for new securi\nties yesterday with the Securities Com\nmission included:\nNational Investors Corp., New York.\no.nOo shares of $1 par value capital\nstock, for Investments. Underwriters to\nbe named later.\nForeign Bond Associates, nc. Jersey\nCity, N. J\u201e investment trust. $1,828.(too\nor 10 cents par value common stock, for\nInvestment. Underwriter, distributors\nGroup, Inc.\nODD-LOT DEALERS.\nThe Securities Commission eported yes\nterday these transactions by customers\nwith odd-lot dealers or specialists cn the\nNew York Stock Exchange for November\n6: 7,702 purchases, involving 100.405\nshares; 5.108 sales, involving 147.659\nshares.\nI\nFARM LAND VALUES UP\n5 BILLION IN 4 YEARS\nAverage Annual Rate of About 4 Per\nCent Is Shown\u2014Half as Large as\nPrevious Decline.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 6.\u2014The value of\nfarm land In the United States has In\ncreased from 30 to more than 35 bil\nlion dollars, or more than 5 billions\nfrom 1933-1937, according to Charles\nL. Stewart of the University of Illinois\nin the current issue of the Annalist.\n\u201cThe farm real estate price advance\nin the country as a whole during the\nfour years has been at an average\nannual rate of about 4 per cent. Ex\npressed in another way, the average\nyearly recovery in farm realty values\nin the country as a whole has been\nat a rate per year slightly more than\nhalf as large as the decline during\nthe 13 years 1920-1933.\n\u201cEstimating the average value of\nfarm real estate per acre in the United\nStates at $29 in 1933. $31 in 1935 and\n$34 in 1937, the recent values, disre\ngarding those that were developed be\ntween 1914 and 1920 and withdrawn\nbetween 1920 and the early \u201930s,\nare in line with the simple upward\ntrend characteristic of the period 1850\n1900, as projected toward 1940, though\nnot high enough to be in line with the\nsteeper simple upward trend of 1880\n1890.\n\"Influences contributing to the re\ncent upswing in farm realty values in\nclude the following: <l) Reduction\nin rates of return investors generally\nwere able to obtain for each $100 of\nfresh capital, thus supporting higher\nvaluations for a given amount of net\nincome; (2) reduction in the amount\nof distress land seeking stronger hands\nto hold it; (3) change in the balance\nbetween land costs, notably taxes and\nreal estate mortgage interest, on the\none hand and gross income from farm\nproduction on the other, so as to make\nnet returns better; (4) participation of\nfarm owners and operators in Federal\nprograms under which rental and\nbenefit payments were poured into\nareas where distress had been especial\nly marked. It is to be noted that Fed\neral payments represented high pro\nportions of real estate valuations in\nSouthern States and may help to ac\ncount for the fact that rates of real\nestate advance were highest in that\nregion.\u201d\nSHARP DOME\nW9 INCOME\nSHOWN IN REPORT\nRustless Iron and Steel of\nBaltimore Declares 621/2\nCents Dividend.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. Nov. 6.\u2014Sharp\nDohme, Inc., drug manufacturer with\nprincipal laboratories in Baltimore\nand branches in leading cities, for the\nquarter ended September 30 reported\nnet income of S170.679 before 1h? Fed\neral undistributed profits surtax, equal\nto 74 cents a share on the $3.50 pre\nferred stock, against $162,190 or 70\ncents a preferred share in the preced\ning quarter and $294,064 or 12 cents\na preferred share in the September,\n1936. quarter.\nRustless Iron Dividend.\nThe Rustless Iron Steel Corp. de\nclared the regular quarterly dividend\nof 62>2 cents on the cumulative con\nvertible preferred stock. President C. I\nE. Tuttle said expansion would be\nfinanced by earnings, not by the pro\nposed issuance of preferred stock.\nCommon stock holders, he said, prob\nably would receive a dividend of pre\nferred stock.\nCreole Corp. Payment.\nDirectors of Creole Petroleum Corp.\ndeclared an extra dividend of 25 cents\na share of capital stock, and a dividend\nof 25 cents, both payable December\n15 to stockholders of record November\n30. Similar payments were made\nJune 10.\nHecla Mining Profit.\nHecla Mining Co., with properties\nin Idaho, reported for the quarter\nended September 30 net profit of $241,\n277. equal to 24 cents a share on the\ncapital stock. This compared with\n$187,886 or 19 cents a share in the\npreceding quarter and $157,561 or\n16 cents a share in the comparable\nperiod last year.\nAmerada Corp. Net.\nAmerada Corp., oil producing com\npany with properties in Western\nStates, reported net profit for the\nquarter ended September 30 of $603,\n772, equal to 76 cents a share on the\ncapital stock. This compared with\n$552,991, or 70 cents a share in the\npreceding quarter and $475,336, or 60\ncents a share in the third quarter of\n1936.\nArcher-Daniels-Midland.\nNet profit or Archer-Daniels-Mid\nland Co. for the third quarter was\nreported at $358,450, equal after pre\nferred dividend requirements to 56\ncents a share, compared with $523,444,\nor 85 cents a share in the like period\nof 1936. The company, producing lin\nseed oil cake and meal, has mills at\n(See EARNINGS, Page E-47)\nWHEAT TUMBLES\nTO 2-YEAR LOW,\nTHEN UBS IIP\nMarket Closes Off About\n3% Cents a Bushel in\nBrisk Selling.\nBv FRANKLIN ML'LLIN,\nAssociated Press Market Writer.\nCHICAGO, Nov. 6.\u2014Dropping as\nmuch as 3*, cents a bushel at one\nstage, wheat prices plunged today to\nthe lowest level in more than two\nyears. Before the close the market\nrecovered about a cent of the extreme\nloss.\nBrisk selling that swept over all\nmajor world markets was attributed\nto discouraged owners, many of whom\napparently placed stop loss orders near\nyesterday's closing prices. A decline\nof 8 to 10 cents at Chicago since the\nfirst of the month depressed long in\nterests while the day's developments\nincluding weakness in stocks and sharp\ndeclines abroad accentuated the sell\ning. The early break brought a large\nvolume of stop loss orders into execu\ntion and the descent was rapid. Short\ncovering by leading professionals who\ntook their profits and buying by cash\ninterests caused the closing rally.\nAt midseason low levels December\nand July wheat were the lowest they\nhave been since July. 1935, while May\nwas its lowest since May, 1935.\nWheat closed 2%-3 cents below Fri\nday's finish, December 86-8S 8, May\n86%-86ss, July 82-82 e; corn was\n\u2019h-\u2019s down, December 55%-55%,\nMay, 57*4-57%, July 58*4: oats\noff, December 29*s; rye 1*4-2 down,\nDecember 66; lard, 7 to 10 cents lower.\nGrain range at principal markets today:\nDECEMBER WHEAT\u2014 Prev.\nHigh. Low. Close. close.\nChicago .8774 .84s, .89 .887,-1,4\nMinneapolis .94 74 .927* .937* .93\u2019,\nKansas City .84 .82\u2019, .83 85\u2019\u00ab-86\nWinnipeg 1.97', 1.047, 1.09s, 1.98',\nLiverpool 1.33 1.21*4 1.217, 1.24 *4\nL'p'l. Mch. 1.17\u2019, 1.19*, 1.101,4 1.191,\nMAY WHEAT\u2014\nChicago .88 .85*, .897', .80-8974\nMinneapolis .937* .91s, ,92s* .95\nKansas City ,83s, .82 .82\u2019, 85',\nWinnipeg 1.95 1.0274 1.94s, 1.997,\nLiverpool 1.19\u2019, 1.15 1.15 1.187,\nExchange. S4.907a.\nJULY WHEAT\u2014\nChicago .84 .81*4 .82 .84\u2019,-85\nMinneapolis .99s, .so'* ,99s, 92\u2019,\nKansas City .787, ,77\u2018a .77\u2018a .80',-7,\nDECEMBER CORN\u2014\nChicago .59 .557, .551* .5RV4-H\nKansas City .53% .53 .5374 .53\u20194-54\nMAY CORN\u2014\nChicago .58 .5774 .577, .58-5874\nKansas City .59 .55*4 .597, .50>,\nDECEMBER OATS\u2014\nChicago .297, .2974 .2974 .39*,\nMinneapolis .297, .29\u2019, .2574 .27\u2019,\nWinnipeg .44*, .43*4 .4374 .44\u2019,\nChicago Cash Market.\nCash wheat. No. 4 red, 83%; No. 5\nmixed, 74*/2. Corn, No. 3 mixed, 53%;\nNo. 2 yellow, 55-56; No. 2 white. 57.\nOats, No. 3 mixed, 31%; No. 1 white,\n32%. No rye. No buckwheat. Soy\nbeans, No. 2 yellow, 92%a%; No. 3 yel\nlow, 91-92%. Barley, feed, 41-62; malt\ning, 60-91. Timothy seed, 2.25-65; red\nclover seed, 27.50-32.50; sweet clover\nseed, 7.00-75.\nHow Is Business?\nShowing Current Business Activity Compared with the Same Week a Year Ago\n___ NOV ore. Jan. Ftt Ma\u00bb. |\u00abp\u00bb may June July aug. Sept. Ocrom\n1936 1937 \u201cl\n+50* --1\nI Present\n+\u26660* Business\n+30*-1 \u2014--J-+5.4%\nGENERAL BUSINESS ACTIVITY for th* country Indicated by Bank Dnblte outalda\nN. Y, City. Shaded areas show week of activity above the corresponding week oftH\nprevious year. Black areas Indicate declines from same weeks twelvemonths earliev*\nACTIVITY BY FEDERAL RESERVE DISTRICTS\nCheck Transactiona compared with the aame week year ago\nftoston iinw York Philadelphia \u00a3levelaad ^iehasonJ itltsu\n\u201411.7% ~5.i% -0.4% +s.3% -i-13.3%\u2014L-\u00b1L13L\nChiaago I St. Lonb Mlnnaapolb I Kanaaa City I Dallaa >.Franaiaoa\n+6.3% I +16351 +5.8% I +11.6* 1 +6.3% I\nLEADING BAROMETERS\nShowing Trend of Important Factor* Chang*\nPreaent Trend From Year Ago\nBusiness in Dollars (Checks Cashed) Downward 5.4\nEmployment (Dept, of Labor). Downward 6.9\nWages (Dept, of Labor). Downward +19.7\nCost of Living (Ind. Conf. Board)... Upward 4.0\nWholesale Prices (Fisher\u2019s Index)... Downward 6.3\nAgricultural Prices (Bureau of Labor) Upward 4.1\nMovement of Goods (Car Loadings). Downward 5,0\nRetail Trade (Fed. Res. Board). Upward 7.9\nBuilding Contracts (F. W. Dodge).. Upward 10.4\nFailures (Dun\u2019s). Upward 19.3\nBond Prices (Dow-Jones). Downward 9.8\nStock Prices (Composite Dow-Jones) Upward 28.0\nStock Mkt. Vol. (Shares Traded).... Downward 4- 31.1\nAlI right* mtntd, Cambridge* Auodatm Bod*\nI I\nSTOCKS TAKE SLIDE\nSTEELS LEAD DROP\nForecast of New Decline in\nOutput Next Week Helps\nSlump.\nCOMMODITIES\u2019 TREND\nDISTURBING INFLUENCE\nRail Liens Sag; in Quiet Bond\nMarket\u2014Curb Issues Are\nDown Fractions.\nBy FREDERICK GARDNER,\nAssociated Press Financial Editor.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 6.\u2014Predictions\nof another sharp drop in steel mill\nproduction next week, combined with\ncloudier trade news elsewhere, put\nstock market leaders on the roller\ncoaster today for a slide of 1 to 4\npoints generally and as much as 7 or\nso in a few instances.\nSteels were easily the leaders in the\nsetback, but coppers, motors, rubbers,\noils, farm implements and miscellane\nous issues were also prominent losers.\nThe trend was lower from the start,\nalthough selling was far from insis\ntent. In the second hour, however,\nofferings expanded sufficiently to put\nthe ticker tape behind for a while. It\nsoon caught up and the pace was only\nmoderate to the close.\nThe Associated Press average of 60\nstocks yielded 1.2 points at 45.5 and\nwas just .4 of a point above the low\nfor the year. Transfers totaled 766.\n390 shares, compared with 713,910 last\nSaturday.\nCommodities Decline.\nFurther softness in commodities was\na disturbing influence. Wheat at Chi\ncago was off 2>i to 3 cents a bushel.\nCom was down to T*. Cotton re\ntreated 20 to 35 cents a bushel. Coffee\nfutures broke to new lows.\nSecondary rail bonds fell to bottom\nlevels since 1933 and other listed loans\nlacked Recovery vigor.\nThe recent buoyant gold shares took\na rest, most stepping into slightly\nlower territory as financial observers\ncontinued to scout foreign rumors\nthat Washington might boost the\nprice of the yellow metal.\nAt the same time bar gold in Lon\ndon and sterling in New York hit new\ntwo-year tops as hoarding abroad\nshowed few signs of diminishing and\nit was reported the British equalisa\ntion fund had acquired gold from\nAmerica. Further repatriation of Euro\npean short-term balances helped de\npress the dollar.\nCoppers were rather sickly on the\nbelief of some in this industry yester\nday's cut of the domestic price to 11\ncents a pound may be extended.\nRails Improve.\nRails acted a little better than\nother groups, excepting utilities, on\nhopec the latest plea for a flat freight\nrate boost will be granted. It was\nalso noted that, in the transporta\ntion economy move, more than 17,\n000 employes of class 1 railroads had\nbeen dropped between September 15\nand October 15.\nWall Street continued to discuss\npossibilities of Congress altering the\nundistributed esrnings and capital\ngains tax laws, but the growing be\nlief this would be done apparently\nwas not converted into a stock-buying\nurge.\nThose who suggest steel output may\nbe dragging bottom at the present\ntime pointed to the recent 47,000-ton\norder by the Ford Motor concern and\nnaval awards of more than $1,000,000\neach to Bethlehem and Midvale.\nBethlehem stock, though, was oft 4%\npoints at 45%.\nOthers prominent on the decline\nwere U. S. Steel at 53. General Elec\ntric, 37%; Chrysler, 67%; General\nMotors, 38!2: American Telephone,\n148%; Anaconda, 25; Kennecott,\n29%; American Smelting, 47; Santa\nFe, 37; American Chain preferred, 88;\nSears, Roebuck, 61%; Montgomery\nWard, 37Vi: J. I. Case. 93; Loews,\n57%; Douglas Aircraft, 31; U. S. Rub\nber, 25%; Du Pont, 115%; Standard\nOil of New Jersey, 49%, and Texas\nCorp., 40%.\nRail Liens Sag.\nRail liens sagged in a quiet bond\nmarket. Other domestic corporate\nliens followed a narrow groove, while\nFederal loans and foreign dollar is\nsues were uneven.\nThe carrier group met'fairly heavy\nselling, particularly lower priced and\ndefaulted obligations. The Associated\nPress averages for 20 rails dropped\n1 t of a point to 73.9, the lowest level\nsince December 27, 1933.\nOther rails pointing down included\nErie refunding 5s at 42%, off 2%,\nMissouri Pacific 5s at 19, off 1, New\nYork Central 3Vis at 83%,_ off 1%\nand Southern Railway 4s at 49, off\n2%.\nUtility and industrial liens held a\nfairly steady course with most losses\nconfined to fractions. The average\nfor 10 industrials dropped .2 of a point\nto 98.4 while 10 utilities were un\nchanged at 92.6. International Tele\nphone 5s slipped a point to 60 and\nPostal Telegraph 5s lost a fraction\nto 12%,.\nCurb Stocks Down.\nLate selling drove curb stocks down\nfractions to around a point in fairly\nheavy dealings for a short session.\nSome higher priced issues were off\nas much as 5 points but, in general,\ndeclines were held to fractions.\nAlmuminum Co. dropped 5% to 85\nand Newmont Mining was down 3\npoints to 60. Down a point or so were\nAmerican Cyanamid \"B\u201d at 235/* and\nAmerican Gas Electric at 24%.\nGulf Oil, a fairly heavy loser in recent\nsessions, slumped 1% to 40.\nLosing fractions were Consolidated\nCopper, 4%, Electric Bond St Share\n9%, Fairchild Aviation 2%, Fisk 6%,\nHudson Bay 19, Humble 57%, Niagara\nHudson Power 8%, 8t. Regis Paper\n3% and United Gas 4%.\nCountering the trend for minor\ngains were Imperial Oil at 18 and In*\ntematlonal Petroleum at 30%.\n\n\nPRICES OF COTTON\nOFF 4 TO 7 POINTS\nMarket Feels Influence of\nSelling in Sympathy With\nStock Trend.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. Nov. 6.\u2014Cotton\nreacted today under liquidation\nprompted by trade expectation* of a\nbearish Government crop estimate on\nMonday. March eased from 7.80 to\n7.71 and closed at 7.75. with final j\nprices 4 to 7 points net lower.\nOpening prices ranged from 1 point\nlower to 2 higher, with easier Liverpool j\ncables offset by firmness of sterling\nexchange. Hedge selling was light,\nbut the market felt the influence of\nscattered selling in sympathy with the\naction of securities. Poor business in\ncotton goods markets was reflected in\nsmaller trade buying, but the recent\ndecline in cotton prices caused offer\nings from the South to dry up.\nPrivate crop estimates range from\n17,000.000 up to 18.109,000 bales and\naveraged 17,490,000. compared with the\nOctober bureau of 17.573,000. Members\nof the New York Cotton Exchange,\nhowever, on the average, are looking\nfor a crop of 17,816,000 bales. The\namount of cotton on shipboard await\ning clearance at the close of the week\nwas estimated at 227,000 bales, against\n123,000 last year and 270,000 two years\nago.\nThe range follows:\n_ High. low Close.\nDecember_ 7.74 7.66 7.70\nJune 7.74 7.66 7.68\nMarch_ 7.80 7.71 7 75\nMay 7.84 7.76 7.80-81\nJuly 7.91 7.82 f 7.84-85\nOctober 8.00 7.91 7.94\nSpot steady: middling. 7.85.\nRESIDENTIAL BUILDING\nCONTINUES ITS SLACK\nSpecial Diapetch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. Nov. 6.\u2014Continued\ndepression in residential building is\nillustrated by pronounced slackening\nin activity since the higher levels\nattained in the first four months of\nthe year says the Index of the New\nYork Trust Co. in its current issue.\nWhile contract awards fQp-the Jan\nuary-September period were 25 per\ncent higher than in the corresponding\nmonths of 1936, September awards\nwere below those of September, 1936,\naccording to the bank review, in com\nparison with awards running 78 per\ncent above last year\u2019s levels from\nJanuary through April,\n\u201cAlthough building has shown pro\ngressive improvement since the al\nmost complete stagnation it experi\nenced during the depth of the de\npression,\u201d the Index states, \u201cit still\nlags far behind other phases of indus\ntrial activity. As one of the most\nImportant elements in the general eco\nnomic picture, it is generally agreed\nthat it must increase very materially\nif recovery Is to continue, and while\nthere are reasons to believe that it\nwill do so, the relatively slow progress\nso far made has proved distinctly\ndisappointing. The conditions neces\nsary for a boom\u2014a housing shortage,\nrising rents and enhanced national\nincomes\u2014would appear to have devel\noped, but in the meantime actual\nbuilding is still retarded by high\ncosts, labor difficulties, and the effect\nupon credit of uncertainty in fiscal\nmatters.\u201d\nDOLLAR GOES DOWN\nIN LONDON DEALINGS\nBy the Associated Press.\nLONDON, Nov. 6.\u2014The United\nStates dollar declined 7-16 of a cent\nunder further selling pressure today.\nThe unit closed $5.00 1-16 to the\npound, compared with sterling at\n$4 99% in New York overnight.\nFrench franca ended 147.1$ to the\npound. acelnst 147.1$ yesterday,\nI\nOctober Sales\nOf Chain Stores\nNear 1936 Levels\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 6.\u2014October sales\nof Nation-wide chain stores ran close\nto 1936 levels, with the gain over last\nyear apparently the lowest, in the ag\ngregate. In many months, first reports\nfrom large merchandising units indi\ncated today.\nReporting companies included:\nWalgreen Co.\u2014Sales \u00bb5,872,643\nagainst $5,529,076 in October, 1936,\nan increase of 8.4 per cent.\nPeoples Drug Stores\u2014$1,904,764\nagainst $1,932,481, a decrease of 1.4\nper cent.\nS. H. Kress Co.\u2014*7,113,521\nagainst $7,306,525, a decrease of 2.6\nper cent.\nSafeway Stores\u2014$29,295,924 against\n*27,060,477, an increase of 8 per cent.\nMcCrory Stores\u2014*3,333.124 against\n*3.510,805, a decrease of 5 per cent.\nG. C. Murphy Co.\u2014*3,895,668\nagainst *3.636,717, an increase of 7.1\nper cent.\n1 Lane Bryant, Inc.\u2014(1,474.302\nagainst *1.406.132, an increase of 8.6\nper cent.\nJ. J. Newberry Co.\u2014*4,475.401\nagainst *4,427,651, an increase of 1\nper cent.\nNON-FERROUS METALS\nDEPRECIATE IN VALUE\nBj the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 6.\u2014All non-fer\nrous metals depreciated in value last\nweek, due in large measure to general\neconomic uncertainty, and especially\nindications of further industrial cur\ntailment in the United States. Ex\ntreme caution marked the attitude of\nbuyers in both the foreign and domes\ntic markets.\nThe demand for copper contracted\non the decline, rather than invited\nconsumer interest. One leading re\nfiner made two reductions in price,\naggregating cent a pound for the\nweek, and the domestic base wound\nup the week at 11 cents a pound,\ndelivered valley; some resales how\never, were understood to have been\ndone at 10% cents a pound, and later\nat 10% cents a pound.\nLead declined cent a pound.\nZinc was inactive and unchanged.\nTin reacted 4% cents a pound.\nPRODUCTION OF SHOES\nDECLINES FOR MONTH\nBy the Associated Press.\nProduction of boots, shoes and slip\npers, other than rubber, totaled 33,\n616,864 pairs in September, compared\nwith 38,562,959 in August and 40,974,\n713 in September last year, the Census\nBureau reports.\nZINC EXPORTS INCREASE.\nExports of zinc and zinc products in\nSeptember amounted to *190,238, com\npared with *170,907 in August and\n1114,027 in September, 1936, the Com\nmerce Department reports.\n1 11 1\nins cut\nSEEN GOOD SIGN\nBusiness Slump Will Not Be\nLong and Drawn Out,\nEconomists Feel.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 6.\u2014The abrupt\ncurtailment of industrial operations\nin the last few months is looked upon\nby some economists as an indication\nthe current business recession will not\nbe a long-drawn-out affair.\nThe steel industry, for instance, is\nreported to be working at around 49 I\nper cent of capacity this week, approx\nimately half the rate existing at the\npeak last spring.\nDuring the early summer steel\nmakers worked on heavy backlogs.\nNew business, however, slowed down\nconsiderably. As unfilled orders ran\nlow, therefore, big producers cut out\nput rather than attempt to anticipate\nan upturn by laying in inventories of\nfinished goods.\nIn October, 30 blast furnaces making\npig iron, the basis of steel, were shut\ndown. More furnaces were blown out\nduring this period than at any time\nsince 1924.\nAvailable data indicate a similar\ndownward trend in other industgal\nlines. Machine tool orders in August\nand September averaged 21 per cent\nunder the recovery high of last March\nand April.\nWith freight loadings slipping fast,\ncarriers cut orders for new equipment.\nIn the same two spring months 19.000\nfreight cars and 113 locomotives were\ncontracted for, while only 2.700 cars\nand 47 steam engines were bought in\nAugust and September.\nThe quick readjustment of the in\ndustrial tempo to a falling off in or\nders is considered a healthy sign by\nmost analysts.\nThe throttling-down process at the\npresent time contrasts sharply with\n1929-30. In this earlier period indus\ntrial leaders responded to appeals to\nkeep up the flow of goods and thereby\nmaintain the purchasing power of\nlabor.\nHUDSON\u2019S SHIPMENTS\nADVANCE 56 PER CENT\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, Nov. 6.\u2014Shipments of\nthe Hudson Motor Car Co. in October\ntotaled 15,269 cars, a gain of 56 per\ncent over the 9.782 cars shipped in\nOctober, 1936. October shipments\nconsisted entirely of 1938 models.\nThe total shipments of 1937 models\nnow completed were 122,791 cars.\nW. R. Tracy, vice president in\ncharge of sales, said an earlier start\nthis year on new model production\nwas in part responsible for the large\nOctober increase. Production sched\nules for early November have been\nset at the October rate.\nWeekly Financial High Lights\nBy the Associated Press. This week. Prev. week. Year ago.\nBroker*\u2019 loans- $732,000 $779,000 $981,000\nHoldings TJ. 8. Securities-,- 2,526,190 2,526,190 2,430,227\nOold reserve. 9,124,896 9,126,391 8,650,837\nRediscounts_ 24,319 23,426 7,077\nBank cfearings. 5,311,305 5,846,201 5,296,277\nElectric output (kilowatt hdwrs)\nweek ended October 30\u2014.. 2,254,947 2,281,636 2,166,656\n(Final three ciphers omitted in above.)\nCar loadings, week ended Oct. 30\u2014. 771,655 773,353 814,514\nCrude oil products (barrels)._ 3,602,950 3,613,300 3,043,500\n9tock sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange... 6,251,230 11,190,090 12,978,010 1\nBond sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange... $35,259,550 $49,016,175 $68,807,000 1\nNew financing 6,580,000 19,058,000 3,342,020\nfederal Reserve ratio_ 80.3% 80.2% 80.1%\n3teel output fate- 48.6% 52.1% 74.7%\nCall money rate- 1% 1% 1% 1\nrime money rata--- t%-iya% iy4-l%% iy4%\nCommercial paper 1% 1%\nt\nTHE BIG APPLE\nI-\u2014-\u2014~\nFURTHER DEW\nr_j\nSteel and Motor Output,\nPower and Carloadings\nRecede Again.\nWEEK\u2019S RETAIL TRADE\nSHOWS MIXED TREND\nWholesale Markets Remain Under\nInfluence of Generally Cau\ntious Buying Demand.\nBv THOMAS E. FLANAGAN,\nAssociated Press Financial Writer.\nThe Nation\u2019s business continued to\ndecline last week.\nThe four major divisions of indus\ntry-steel output, motor production,\nelectric power and railroad carloadings\n\u2014again fell back a little.\nMeanwhile, cuts in production were\nrecorded by makers of shoes, textiles,\ntires and other consumers goods as\norders dwindled and distributors\nplanned to keep inventories down to\nworkable levels.\n\"The closing days of October and\nthe first few days of November brought\na mixed trend in retail trade for the\nfirst time in several weeks.\u201d the De\npartment of Commerce reported in its\nweekly survey of 27 cities.\n\"In some 15 important cities business\nslumped compared with the same time\nlast year, while an equal number re\nported a good week and substantial\nincreases over the comparable 1936\nperiod.\nCautious Buying Demand.\n\"Wholesale markets were under the\ninfluence of the generally cautious\nbuying demand which has been evi\ndent recently. The general situation\nwas well epitomized in the report from\n-New York which said, \"It must be\nborne in mind that comparisons are\nnow directed against a period of last\nyear when business was abnormally\nhigh due to the double fear of rapidly\nrising prices and shortage of goods.\u201d\nThe Associated Press index of in\ndustrial activity dropped to 90.3 from\n92.6 the previous week. In the like\n1936 week it stood at 96.2.\nThe steel industry operating rate\nreceded to 48.6 per cent of capacity\nfrom 52.1 the preceding week, accord\ning to the estimate of the American\nIron and Steel Institute. A month ago\nit was 66.1, a year ago 74.7.\nThe downturn, experts said, was a\nfurther adjustment to the small\nvolume of new business. Although\nit was felt the speed of the down\nswing in new buying has been\nchecked, the outlook for a brisk up\nturn has been dimmed by the hand\nto-mouth buying of the automobile\nindustry\u2019.\nWithhold Judgment.\nLittle help was to be had from\neither the railroad or building con\nstruction industries, leading takers of\nheavy steels. Whether the motor\ndivision would soon step into the\nbreach with orders, in the last\nanalysis, depends on the reception\ngiven to new automobile models by\nthe public, well-informed steel men\nsaid.\nOn the latter question motor ob\nservers withheld judgment. It was\nnoted that the industry turned out\nfewer cars\u201489,770, compared with\n90,155 the week previous and 84.780\nin the like week a year ago, Ward's\nreported.\nThe problem of retail consumption\nof new cars, it was argued, hung\non the ability of the public to buy\nmotors at the higher prices, in spite\nof lower purchasing power in some\nregions.\nThat the automobile industry Itself\nwas keenly aware of the problem was\nseen in reports studies of price re\nvisions were under way w'ith a view\nto overcoming sales resistance to\nhigher prices. While no general\nprice cuts were said to be in sight,\nit was believed reductions might be\nposted by some makers in order to\njockey into more suitable competitive\nposition;\nPower Output Drops.\nOutput of electric power In the\nweek ended October 30 slumped more\nthan seasonally, power analysts said.\nThe total, reported by the Edison\nElectric Institute, was 2,254,947,000\nkilowatt hours, a modest cut from\nthe preceding week, but 4.1 per cent\nabove the like week last year.\nFurther reduction in the rate of\ngain over 1936 continued to arrest at\ntention. The slackening in the de\nmand for power was again most pro\nnounced in the leading Industrial\nareas. For instance, consumption of\nelectricity in New England was 2 per\ncent under the 1936 week, whereas\nin the week ended October 23 it was\nup 0.7 of 1 per cent over last year.\nSizable downswings in the margin of\ngain were also recorded in the central\nindustrial and Middle Atlantic regions.\nRail shipments of freight also served\nto confirm indications of a slower pace\nof business, particularly in heavy In\ndustrial activity. The Association of\nAmerican Railroads reported loadings\nin the week ended October 30 at 771,\n655, down 0.2 of 1 per cent from the\nprevious week and off 5.3 per cent\nfrom the corresponding week of 1936.\nMaking for contraction in the to\ntal amount of freight hauled were\nmoderate declines in shipments of ore\nand coal. On the other hand, the\nsmall increase in miscellaneous freight\nindicated many products were moving\nthrough channels of trade and indus\ntry faster than at this time last year.\nModerate Turnover.\nThe stock market declined on mod\nerate turnover after the preceding\nweek\u2019s sharp upswing. Wall Street\nnen said third quarter reports coming\nhand showed clearly how higher\n3perating costs have eaten into profits,\nrhis, together with general business\n\u2022ecessions and uncertainties on farm\nind wages and hours legislation had\nieprived the market of support.\nBonds were down under the weight\n>f the same factors affecting shares,\ninancial men said. Rail loans were\nmffeted. United States Government\n)bligatlons were in demand most of\n(See INDUSTRY, Page E-3.)\n1\nw/i/","height":"31188","width":"22272"}}
